Li et al. have used thiourea and neutral red to synthesize red fluorescent carbon dots for Au3+ detection by using colorimetric detection and fluorescent spectral response within 2 min with a lower detection limit of 29 nM (excitation at 520 nm and emission at 637 nm) (Table 1
                        ). The as-prepared CDs have great selectivity when other interfering metal ions are present in high concentration without compromising the intensity of fluorescence emission. So, the synthesized CDs displayed high sensitivity and selectivity towards Au3+ 
                        [12].

Li et al. prepared surface-engineered NIR-responsive carbon dots using poly(vinylpyrrolidone) (PVP). These carbon dots were then utilized as an in vivo real-time bioimaging agent in the stomach of mice, employing 732 nm laser excitation (
                        Table 4

                        ). Consequently, a strong NIR fluorescence signal emanated from the PVP-carbon dots within the mice’s stomach. This observation led to the conclusion that PVP-carbon dots are capable of producing a fluorescence signal within the NIR region, allowing for the real-time visualization of their distribution in the mice’s stomach. The utilization of an 800 nm long-pass optical filter facilitated this visualization (
                        Fig. 3

                        ).

In a study by Lan et al. NIR-responsive carbon dots were investigated as a two-photon fluorescence bioimaging agent in HeLa cells (
                        Table 4
                        ). Bioimaging in HeLa cells was conducted using two-photon laser scanning confocal microscopy after an 8-hour incubation with carbon dots. This revealed a distinct red fluorescence signal upon excitation at 880 nm. Additionally, the authors noted a change in cell morphology: blisters had formed around the cells after 3 min of laser irradiation. This observation led the authors to conclude that the prepared carbon dots can induce apoptosis in cells [30].

Liu et al. synthesized carbon dots using large conjugated perylene derivatives, followed by subsequent surface modification using polyethyleneimine (PEI) (
                        Table 4
                        ). These modified carbon dots were then investigated as agents for in vivo NIR bioimaging in mice. Under 690 nm excitation, a vivid NIR fluorescence signal was observed. Remarkably, after 1 h of gavage injection, an intense and bright NIR fluorescence signal was detected, reaching a signal-to-noise ratio of up to 18. This was accompanied by excellent biocompatibility and impressive deep-tissue penetration capability. However, it’s noteworthy that the NIR fluorescence signals diminished from the mice’s body (
                        Fig. 6

                        ) after 28 h following the gavage injection [31].

Bao et al. synthesized sulfur (S) and nitrogen (N) co-doped NIR carbon dots using a solvothermal method, as outlined in Table 4. Their study delved into the distribution and biocompatibility of these carbon dots within major organs (heart, liver, spleen, lung, and kidneys) and urine of mice. This investigation employed NIR fluorescence bioimaging under 639–––713 nm excitation. Following intravenous injection, a strong NIR signal promptly emanated from the liver and kidney after just 30 min. Remarkably, the kidney signal surpassed that of the liver, and both signals vanished entirely within 24 h. These observations indicated a pronounced distribution of carbon dots within the kidney post-injection. Turning attention to urine, pre- and post-injection samples were collected and subjected to NIR fluorescence bioimaging with the same system. A remarkable absence of signal was evident in the pre-injection urine, while intense signal emerged after 30 min of injection. This signal continued to rise over the subsequent hour, before declining and disappearing completely within 24 h. Both investigations led to the conclusion that the prepared carbon dots exhibited remarkable biocompatibility with minimal biotoxicity. This inference was supported by the rapid excretion of the carbon dots from the kidney following intravenous injection. Expanding the investigation to tumor diagnosis and treatment, the distribution of the prepared carbon dots was studied in mice with H22 tumors, serving as a tumor model for in vivo NIR bioimaging (
                        Table 4
                        ). The highest NIR fluorescence signal manifested after 3 h of injection. This signal exhibited gradual elevation from 2 to 3 h, followed by a subsequent decline. This investigation concluded that the highest distribution of carbon dots within the tumor area occurred around 3 h post-injection, potentially due to enhanced permeability and retention effects via blood circulation [27].

Bao et al. synthesized sulphur (S) and nitrogen (N) co-doped near-infrared (NIR) carbon dots through a solvothermal method. The maximum absorption and emissive peak of these NIR carbon dots were observed at 600 nm and 720 nm, respectively. The authors explored the potential of using these carbon dots for in vivo photoacoustic (PA) imaging in a tumor model, specifically mice with 4 T1 tumors. As a result, analysis of photoacoustic maximum amplitude projection images and B-Scan photoacoustic images revealed that the distribution of carbon dots within the tumor cells was uniform, resulting in intense PA signals through the blood circulation. After 3 h of intravenous injection of the carbon dots, the authors observed the strongest PA signals originating from the tumor cells. Additionally, a similar investigation was carried out on mice with HepG2 tumors, and the researchers observed that the prepared carbon dots effectively functioned as NIR-light-triggered in vivo PA imaging agents (
                        Fig. 8

                        ). Based on these findings, the authors concluded that the synthesized carbon dots are highly efficient and safe for use in PA imaging applications [27].
